      ],
      "scripts": [
        {
          "number": 1,
          "script": "Welcome to this lesson on using AI in client reports safely. AI tools are becoming really popular for speeding up report writing, and it's easy to see why. They can save you a lot of time. But there are some genuine risks that are worth understanding before you dive in. Two of the biggest concerns are data privacy and accuracy. If you paste client information into a public AI tool, that data could be exposed in ways you might not expect. And if you rely on AI output without checking it carefully, mistakes can slip through and end up in front of your clients. Not ideal. So in this lesson, we're going to walk through those risks clearly and, importantly, show you how to avoid them. The good news is you do not need any previous experience with AI to follow along. We're starting from the beginning and keeping things practical throughout. Let's get started."
        },
        {
          "number": 2,
          "script": "So before we dive into the how, let's talk about the why, because this really does matter. When a client shares their financial details, personal circumstances, or sensitive business information with you, they're placing a huge amount of trust in you. And that trust is fragile. If you use an AI tool carelessly, that data could end up somewhere it absolutely should not be. On top of that, AI tools can sometimes generate information that simply isn't true. It might look convincing, but if a fabricated figure makes its way into a client report, it could seriously damage your credibility and, more importantly, lead your client to make a poor decision. There are also real legal and regulatory risks around confidentiality that you need to be aware of. The good news is that with a bit of knowledge and care, you can use AI effectively and responsibly. That's exactly what this course is here to help you do."
        },
        {
          "number": 3,
          "script": "So before we look at how to use AI well in client reports, we need to be honest about what can go wrong. And there are a few things worth being aware of. First, AI can simply make things up. It might state a statistic or a fact with complete confidence, when actually that information is entirely fabricated. This is sometimes called hallucination, and it is more common than you might expect. On top of that, if you are pasting client information into an AI tool, there is a real risk that sensitive data could be exposed or stored in ways you have not agreed to. And here is the part that makes this particularly tricky: the output usually looks polished and professional. There are no obvious warning signs. Errors do not announce themselves. So without careful checking, a convincing-sounding mistake could end up in a client report, potentially breaching confidentiality or simply giving your client wrong information. That is why understanding these risks is so important."
        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "script": "Before you paste anything into an AI tool, you need to strip out anything that could identify your client. That means the obvious stuff like names, email addresses, phone numbers, and account references, but also the less obvious details like job titles, team names, or a unique project name that someone could trace back to a specific person or organisation. Even small details can give things away when you put them together, so it is worth being thorough. Now, I know what you might be thinking: if I remove all of that, how do I put the right details back in afterwards? The answer is simple. Keep a private mapping document, something just for your own reference, that records what you replaced and with what. So \"Client A\" maps back to the actual client name, and so on. That way you can swap everything back in accurately once the AI has done its job, and your final report still reads correctly."
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "script": "Before you paste anything into an AI tool, you need to strip out anything that could identify your client. That means names go first, obviously, but it does not stop there. Specific figures, job titles, locations, even dates can all act as identifying details, especially if someone were to piece them together. So replace sensitive numbers with something generic like \"X\" or \"a six-figure sum,\" swap out job titles for broader descriptions, and think carefully about whether a location or timeframe makes the data traceable back to a real person or organisation. The habit I would encourage you to build is a quick review every single time before you hit paste. Not just the first time you use a tool, but every time. It only takes a moment, and it is that moment that keeps you on the right side of your professional obligations and, more importantly, keeps your clients safe."
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "script": "So you've got your AI-generated draft in front of you. What do you do next? The most important habit you can build is this: never just accept what the AI has written without checking it first. AI tools can sound incredibly confident, even when they're completely wrong. They might get a client's name slightly off, misquote a figure, or state something as fact that simply isn't accurate. So go through the output carefully. Verify every factual claim. Double-check names, dates, and numbers in particular, because those are the details that clients will notice immediately if they're wrong. And here's something worth remembering: AI has no knowledge of your specific client relationship. Your own notes, your memory of conversations, your professional judgement, those are your most reliable sources. Use the AI output as a starting point, not a finished product. Your expertise is what makes the report trustworthy, so always let that lead the way."
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "script": "Before you copy a single word of AI output into a client document, stop and read the whole thing through. I mean every sentence. Check any facts, figures, or names against your original source material, because AI can sound very confident while being completely wrong. This is sometimes called hallucination, where the model invents statistics, makes up citations, or produces claims that sound plausible but simply are not true. While you are reading, also pay attention to tone. Does it sound like your firm, or does it feel a bit off? And here is something people often overlook: make sure no details from a different client project have crept into the response, especially if you have been using the same tool across multiple pieces of work. Finally, if you can, ask a colleague to give it a quick read as well. A fresh pair of eyes will almost always catch something that a tired reviewer misses. Never submit without that final check."
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
          "script": "So before we wrap up this lesson, let's bring everything together into a handful of principles you'll want to keep in mind every time you use AI in your reporting work. First and most importantly, never drop real client information directly into an AI tool. Always anonymise it beforehand, swapping out names, addresses, or any identifying details. Once you've got a response back from the AI, don't just accept it at face value. Read it carefully, because AI can get things wrong, and in a professional report, accuracy really matters. It's also worth remembering that the responsibility sits with you. The AI is a helper, not the author. You are the one signing off on that document, so you need to own the final check. That means reviewing what the AI has produced, editing it to match your voice and the facts of the case, and only then submitting it. Keep those habits consistent, and you'll use AI confidently and responsibly."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
